Off-target suppression: spirv-tools-friendlynamemapper-overflow (bucket: oom)

Off-target (issue #6756): libFuzzer out-of-memory via spvtools::FriendlyNameMapper.
With SPV_BINARY_TO_TEXT_OPTION_FRIENDLY_NAMES, ParseInstruction builds human-readable
type names by concatenating the names of component/child types
(OpTypeVector/Matrix/Array/Pointer/...: `_arr_<name(w2)>_<name(w3)>` etc.) and stores
them via SaveName (source/name_mapper.cpp:83). Adversarial nested/recursive type
structures make each level concatenate two already-large child names, so the generated
name length grows super-linearly (effectively doubling per level) into multi-GB strings
from a tiny 431-byte module -> OOM. The allocation top frame is
std::string::_M_construct via NameForId (name_mapper.cpp:58) <- ParseInstruction
(name_mapper.cpp:253). There is no bound on the generated-name size.

Mechanism (minimal bound on name-map growth): cap the stored friendly-name length in
SaveName. Because every name fed back into NameForId (and thus into the next level's
concatenation) is now bounded, the super-linear propagation is broken: each generation
produces a temporary of at most ~2*MAX bytes which is then truncated back to MAX before
storage, so total memory is bounded by (#ids * MAX). Friendly names are cosmetic
disassembly identifiers; truncating pathologically long ones does not change any program
result. 1024 bytes is far larger than any real type/OpName identifier.

This does NOT touch the preset path: the preset heap-buffer-overflow is an out-of-bounds
READ of inst.words[] in ParseInstruction (OpTypePointer arm, name_mapper.cpp:268) on a
short word-count instruction, which occurs while *forming* the suggested_name argument,
before SaveName is entered. SaveName's length cap cannot affect it, so the preset bug
still faults (P2).

--- a/source/name_mapper.cpp
+++ b/source/name_mapper.cpp
@@ -78,7 +78,16 @@ void FriendlyNameMapper::SaveName(uint32_t id,
                                   const std::string& suggested_name) {
   if (name_for_id_.find(id) != name_for_id_.end()) return;
 
-  const std::string sanitized_suggested_name = Sanitize(suggested_name);
+  std::string sanitized_suggested_name = Sanitize(suggested_name);
+  // Off-target OOM guard: bound the generated friendly-name length so that
+  // adversarial nested/recursive type structures cannot drive super-linear
+  // (effectively exponential) name growth into multi-GB allocations. Stored
+  // names feed NameForId at the next concatenation level, so bounding the
+  // stored name bounds the whole chain. Friendly names are cosmetic
+  // disassembly identifiers; truncating pathologically long ones is harmless.
+  constexpr size_t kMaxFriendlyNameLength = 1024;
+  if (sanitized_suggested_name.size() > kMaxFriendlyNameLength)
+    sanitized_suggested_name.resize(kMaxFriendlyNameLength);
   std::string name = sanitized_suggested_name;
   auto inserted = used_names_.insert(name);
   if (!inserted.second) {
 
